Oskar Gottlieb Blarr (born 6 May 1934) is a German composer, organist, church musician and academic teacher.
Blarr was born in Sandlack near Bartenstein (East Prussia).
Blarr was born in Sandlack near Bartenstein (East Prussia).
Blarr was born in Sandlack near Bartenstein (East Prussia).
Blarr and his family fled to West Germany in 1945.
He studied church music from 1952 at the Kirchenmusikschule in Hannover, percussion at the Musikhochschule Hannover, and composition with Heinrich Spitta.

He continued his studies, conducting with Dean Dixon and Herbert von Karajan in Salzburg, composition with Bernd Alois Zimmermann in Cologne, Krzysztof Penderecki at the Folkwang-Hochschule in Essen, and Milko Kelemen and Günther Becker at the Robert Schumann Hochschule.

He continued his studies, conducting with Dean Dixon and Herbert von Karajan in Salzburg, composition with Bernd Alois Zimmermann in Cologne, Krzysztof Penderecki at the Folkwang-Hochschule in Essen, and Milko Kelemen and Günther Becker at the Robert Schumann Hochschule.
He was the church musician of the Neanderkirche in Düsseldorf from 1961 to 1999.
He also set many songs of the genre Neues Geistliches Lied to music, some of under the pseudonym Choral Brother Ogo.
Blarr visited Israel to experience where Jesus lived as a Jew.
